40.	What changes came in HashMap after Java 8?
In Java 8, HashMap improved collision handling by converting linked lists into Red-Black trees 
when the bucket size exceeds a threshold, reducing worst-case complexity from O(n) to O(log n).aaaaaaaa1qwe

✅ How Does Collision Handling Improve in Java 8?
In Java 8, HashMap improved collision handling by switching from a linked list-only approach to a combination of Linked List and Red-Black Tree.
🔹 Before Java 8
•	Collisions handled using Linked List
•	If many elements fall into the same bucket: 
o	List becomes long
o	Lookup time becomes O(n) (poor performance)
🔹 After Java 8 (Improvement)
✅ 1. Treeification (Key Change)
•	If the number of elements in a bucket exceeds 8 (TREEIFY_THRESHOLD): 
o	Linked list is converted into a Red-Black Tree
✔ Time complexity improves:
•	O(n) → O(log n)
✅ 2. Untreeification
•	If elements reduce below 6 (UNTREEIFY_THRESHOLD): 
o	Tree converts back to Linked List
✅ 3. Capacity Condition
•	Tree conversion happens only if: 
o	HashMap capacity ≥ 64 (MIN_TREEIFY_CAPACITY)
•	Otherwise, resizing is preferred

🔹 How It Improves Performance
•	Faster search, insert, delete
•	Handles high collision scenarios efficiently
•	Prevents worst-case degradation
________________________________________
🔹 Flow
Collision occurs
   ↓
Small bucket → Linked List
   ↓ (size > 8)
Convert to Red-Black Tree
   ↓
Faster operations (O(log n))

