5. Exception Handling
----------------------------
•	Difference: Checked vs Unchecked exception

o	Checked exception
o	-----------------------
o	Checked exceptions are exceptions that are checked at compile-time by the Java compiler for smooth execution.
o	If a method throws a checked exception, it must either handle the exception using a try-catch block or 
o	declare the exception using the throws keyword in the method signature. If neither is done, the code will not compile.
o	Examples:
o	IOException
o	SQLException
o	FileNotFoundException
o	ClassNotFoundException
o	
o	Key Characteristics:
o	Must be explicitly handled or declared.
o	Represents conditions that a reasonable application might want to catch (e.g., file not found, network issues).
o	public class CheckedExceptionExample {
o	    public static void main(String[] args) {
o	        try {
o	            File file = new File("nonexistentfile.txt");
o	            FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(file);
o	        } catch (IOException e) {
o	            System.out.println("Caught IOException: " + e.getMessage());
o	        }
o	    }
o	}
o	Unchecked exception
o	--------------------
o	Unchecked exceptions are exceptions that are not checked at compile-time. 
o	They are subclasses of RuntimeException and can occur during the execution of the program. Since the compiler does not check them, 
o	it’s not mandatory to catch or declare them.
o	Examples:
o	NullPointerException
