✅ What is Entity Lifecycle in JPA/Hibernate? (Interview Answer)
The Entity Lifecycle defines the different states an entity (Java object) goes through during its interaction with the persistence context (database).
🔹 Main States of Entity Lifecycle
1. Transient State
•	The object is created but not yet saved to the database
•	Not associated with Hibernate/JPA session
User user = new User(); // Transient
________________________________________
2. Persistent State
•	The object is saved and managed by the persistence context
•	Any changes are automatically synchronized with the database
entityManager.persist(user); // Persistent
________________________________________
3. Detached State
•	The object was persistent but no longer associated with session
•	Changes are not automatically saved
entityManager.detach(user);
``
________________________________________
4. Removed State
•	The object is marked for deletion
•	Will be removed from the database
entityManager.remove(user);
________________________________________
🔁 Lifecycle Flow
Transient → Persistent → Detached → Removed

difference between persist() and merge()
Both persist() and merge() are used to save/update entities, but they behave differently based on the entity state.

🔹 persist()
•	Used to save a new entity
•	Works only with transient objects
•	Converts entity → Persistent state
•	Does not return anything
•	Throws error if entity already exists
✅ Example:
Java
User user = new User(); // Transient
entityManager.persist(user); // Now Persistent
Show more lines
________________________________________
🔹 merge()
•	Used to update an existing entity
•	Works with detached objects
•	Returns a managed (new) entity instance
•	Copies data from given object into managed object
✅ Example:
Java
User detachedUser = new User();
detachedUser.setId(1);

User managedUser = entityManager.merge(detachedUser);

🔁 Key Differences
Feature	persist()	merge()
Purpose	Insert new record	Update existing record
Works with	Transient entities	Detached entities
Return type	void	Returns managed entity
Behavior	Makes same object persistent	Creates new managed copy
If entity exists	Error	Updates existing

🎯 Short Interview Answer
persist() is used to insert a new entity and make it persistent, while merge() is used to update a detached entity and returns a managed copy of it.

