1. Distributed Tracing
Distributed tracing tracks a request as it flows through multiple microservices.
•	It helps identify performance bottlenecks and failures.
•	Each request is assigned a unique trace ID, allowing you to see the entire journey across services.
________________________________________
2. Centralized Logging
Centralized logging collects logs from multiple services into a single system (e.g., ELK stack).
•	Makes debugging easier by providing a unified view.
•	Helps in monitoring, troubleshooting, and auditing.
________________________________________
3. Config Server
A config server is a centralized service that manages configuration for multiple applications.
•	Stores settings (DB URLs, APIs, feature flags) outside the code.
•	Enables dynamic updates without redeploying applications.
________________________________________
4. Saga Pattern
Saga pattern manages distributed transactions across microservices.
•	Instead of a single transaction, it uses a sequence of local transactions.
•	If something fails, compensating actions roll back previous steps.
Two types:
•	Choreography (event-driven)
•	Orchestration (central coordinator)
________________________________________
5. Eventual Consistency
Eventual consistency means data will become consistent over time across services.
•	There is no guarantee of immediate consistency.
•	Common in distributed systems to improve performance and availability.
________________________________________
6. CAP Theorem
CAP states that a distributed system can guarantee only two of the three:
•	Consistency (C) – same data everywhere
•	Availability (A) – system always responds
•	Partition Tolerance (P) – works despite network failures
In practice, systems choose between:
•	CP (Consistency + Partition tolerance)
•	AP (Availability + Partition tolerance)
________________________________________
7. Bulkhead Pattern
Bulkhead isolates parts of a system to prevent failure spreading.
•	Like compartments in a ship.
•	If one service fails, others continue functioning.
________________________________________
8. Rate Limiting
Rate limiting restricts the number of requests a client can make.
•	Prevents system overload and abuse.
•	Example: Allow only 100 requests per minute per user.
________________________________________
9. Idempotency in Microservices
An operation is idempotent if repeating it produces the same result.
•	Prevents duplicate processing (e.g., payment or order creation).
•	Commonly implemented using idempotency keys.
________________________________________
10. Blue-Green Deployment
A deployment strategy with two environments:
•	Blue: current version
•	Green: new version
Traffic switches from blue to green after validation.
•	Enables zero downtime deployments
•	Easy rollback by switching back

