2.	Types of indexes?
3.	Primary Index: Automatically created when a primary key is defined. Ensures that data in the indexed columns is unique and helps quickly locate rows.
4.	Unique Index: Ensures that all values in the indexed column(s) are unique.
5.	Non-Unique Index: Speeds up retrieval operations but does not enforce uniqueness.
6.	Composite Index: Created on multiple columns, allowing searches based on multiple criteria.
7.	Full-Text Index: Used for full-text searches within text data.
8.	Clustered Index: Sorts and stores the data rows in the table based on their key values. Each table can have only one clustered index.
9.	Non-Clustered Index: Creates a separate structure from the data rows. Each table can have multiple non-clustered indexes.

10.	Difference between clustered and non-clustered index?
11.	Feature	12.	Clustered Index	13.	Non-Clustered Index
14.	Data storage	15.	Determines the physical order of data in the table	16.	Stores a separate structure pointing to data
17.	Number per table	18.	Only one	19.	Can have multiple
20.	Data location	21.	Data is stored in the same structure as the index	22.	Index contains pointers (row locators) to actual data
23.	Performance	24.	Faster for range queries and sorting	25.	Faster for lookup queries
26.	Leaf nodes	27.	Contains actual table data	28.	Contains index key + pointer to data
