UNION ALL
SELECT Name FROM Managers;
________________________________________
✅ Difference
Feature	UNION	UNION ALL
Duplicates	❌ Removed	✅ Allowed
Performance	Slower	Faster
Use case	Unique data needed	All data needed
________________________________________
2. What is EXISTS?
✅ Definition:
EXISTS checks if a subquery returns any row
•	Returns TRUE if at least one record exists
________________________________________
✅ Example:
SELECT Name
FROM Employees e
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT 1
    FROM Departments d
    WHERE e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID
);
👉 Returns employees only if matching department exists
________________________________________
3. What is Subquery?
✅ Definition:
A subquery is a query inside another SQL query.
________________________________________
✅ Example:
SELECT Name
FROM Employees
WHERE Salary > (
    SELECT AVG(Salary)
    FROM Employees
);
👉 Finds employees earning above average salary
________________________________________
✅ Types:
•	Single-row subquery
•	Multi-row subquery
•	Correlated subquery
________________________________________
4. What is Stored Procedure?
✅ Definition:
A stored procedure is a precompiled set of SQL statements stored in the database that can be executed when needed.
________________________________________
✅ Example:
CREATE PROCEDURE GetEmployees
AS
BEGIN
    SELECT * FROM Employees;
END;
👉 Call using:
EXEC GetEmployees;
________________________________________
✅ Benefits:
•	✅ Improves performance
•	✅ Reusable code
•	✅ Better security
•	✅ Reduces network traffic
________________________________________
5. What is Alias?
✅ Definition:
An alias is a temporary name given to a table or column in a query.
________________________________________
✅ Example (Column Alias):
SELECT Name AS EmployeeName
FROM Employees;
________________________________________
✅ Example (Table Alias):
SELECT e.Name
FROM Employees e;
________________________________________
✅ Benefits:
•	Makes query shorter and readable
•	Useful in joins
________________________________________
✅ Quick Summary
•	UNION → removes duplicates
•	UNION ALL → keeps duplicates (faster)
•	EXISTS → checks if subquery returns rows
•	Subquery → query inside another query
•	Stored Procedure → reusable SQL block
•	Alias → temporary name for table/column
________________________________________

1. Why is index not always good?
Indexes improve read performance but have drawbacks:
•	❌ Slows down INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE → index must be updated
•	❌ Consumes extra storage space
•	❌ Over-indexing reduces performance
•	❌ Not useful for small tables
•	❌ Inefficient for low-cardinality columns (e.g., Gender)
✅ Conclusion: Indexes are a trade-off (fast reads vs slow writes)
________________________________________

2. Why GROUP BY is used with aggregate functions?
Aggregate functions (SUM, COUNT, AVG, etc.) calculate values over multiple rows.
👉 GROUP BY is used to:
•	Divide data into groups
•	Apply aggregate function per group
Example:
SELECT Department, COUNT(*)
FROM Employees
GROUP BY Department;
``
👉 Without GROUP BY → only one overall result
👉 With GROUP BY → result per department
________________________________________
3. Why HAVING is needed?
HAVING is used to filter aggregated results.
👉 Because WHERE cannot use aggregate functions.
Example:
SELECT Department, COUNT()
FROM Employees
GROUP BY Department
HAVING COUNT() > 5;
👉 Filters groups after aggregation
________________________________________
________________________________________
5. What happens if you use DELETE without WHERE?
DELETE FROM Employees;
``
🚨 Result:
•	Deletes ALL rows in the table
•	Table structure remains intact
⚠️ Very risky operation
________________________________________
6. Why TRUNCATE is faster than DELETE?
Feature	DELETE	TRUNCATE
Operation type	Row-by-row	Removes all data at once
Logging	Fully logged	Minimal logging
WHERE clause	✅ Supported	❌ Not supported
Speed	Slower	Faster
✅ Reason:
TRUNCATE deallocates pages instead of deleting row-by-row
__________________________________________
8. How JOIN works internally?
Internally, databases use algorithms like:
✅ Common Join Methods:
1.	Nested Loop Join
o	Compare each row of one table with another
2.	Hash Join
o	Uses hash table for faster matching
3.	Merge Join
o	Works on sorted data
👉 Optimizer chooses best method based on:
•	Table size
•	Index availability
•	Query conditions
________________________________________
9. Why NULL is not equal to anything?
✅ NULL represents unknown/missing value
👉 So:
NULL = NULL   → FALSE
NULL != NULL  → FALSE
✔ Correct way:
IS NULL
IS NOT NULL
👉 Because unknown cannot be compared
________________________________________
10. Why FULL JOIN not available in some DBs?
Some databases (like older MySQL versions) don’t support FULL JOIN because:
•	It is complex to implement efficiently
•	Less frequently used compared to INNER/LEFT JOIN
•	Can be simulated using UNION
Alternative:
SELECT * FROM A
LEFT JOIN B ON A.id = B.id
UNION
SELECT * FROM A
RIGHT JOIN B ON A.id = B.id;
________________________________________
✅ Quick Summary
•	Indexes → improve reads but slow writes
•	GROUP BY → groups data for aggregation
•	HAVING → filters aggregated results
•	WHERE vs HAVING → before vs after grouping
•	DELETE without WHERE → removes all data
•	TRUNCATE → faster due to minimal logging
•	PRIMARY KEY vs UNIQUE → NULL + count difference
•	JOIN → uses internal algorithms (nested loop, hash, merge)
•	NULL → unknown, cannot be compared
•	FULL JOIN → missing in some DBs, can use UNION
________________________________________
