✅ 1. Why is String immutable?
👉 Reasons:
•	✅ Security (used in URLs, file paths, DB connections)
•	✅ Thread-safe (no synchronization needed)
•	✅ String Pool optimization (memory efficient)
•	✅ Caching hashCode (performance for HashMap)
String s = "Java";
s.concat("World"); // creates new object, original unchanged
👉 Immutability = value cannot change once created
________________________________________
✅ 2. Why should HashMap key be immutable?
👉 Reason: Consistency of hashing
•	HashMap uses: 
•	
o	hashCode() → find bucket
o	equals() → compare key
❌ If key changes after insertion:
•	Hash code changes
•	Object goes to wrong bucket
•	Retrieval fails
✅ Example:
map.put(key, "value");
// if key changes → map.get(key) may return null
``
👉 Therefore keys should be immutable (e.g., String)
________________________________________
✅ 3. Why override equals() & hashCode() together?
👉 Rule: ✅ If equals() is true → hashCode() MUST be same
👉 Used by:
•	HashMap
•	HashSet
❌ If only equals() overridden:
•	Objects considered equal
•	But stored in different buckets
✅ Result → duplicate entries / wrong behavior
________________________________________
✅ 4. Why multiple inheritance is not allowed (classes)?
👉 To avoid ambiguity (Diamond Problem)
Example:
class A { void show() {} }
class B extends A {}
class C extends A {}
class D extends B, C {} // ❌ Not allowed
👉 Which show() should be called?
✅ Confusion → avoided in Java
✔ Instead:
•	Use interfaces (supports multiple inheritance)
________________________________________
✅ 5. Difference between Fail-Fast and Fail-Safe
Feature	Fail-Fast	Fail-Safe
Behavior	Throws exception	Works on copy
Exception	✅ ConcurrentModificationException	❌ No exception
Example	ArrayList, HashMap	CopyOnWriteArrayList
Modification allowed	❌ No	✅ Yes
👉 Fail-fast detects changes immediately
👉 Fail-safe allows safe iteration
________________________________________
✅ 6. synchronized vs ReentrantLock
Feature	synchronized	ReentrantLock
Lock handling	Automatic	Manual
Flexibility	Less	More
tryLock()	❌ No	✅ Yes
Interruptible	❌ No	✅ Yes
Fairness	❌ No	✅ Yes
👉 ReentrantLock = advanced version of synchronized
________________________________________
✅ 7. Why ConcurrentHashMap is faster than Hashtable?
👉 Key reasons:
•	✅ Fine-grained locking (segment-based / bucket-level)
•	❌ Hashtable locks entire map (coarse locking)
👉 Result:
•	Multiple threads access different parts simultaneously ✅
•	Better performance 🚀
________________________________________
✅ 8. Why wait() is in Object class (not Thread)?
👉 Because:
•	wait() works on object monitor (lock), not thread
synchronized(obj) {
    obj.wait();
}
👉 Every object has a lock (monitor)
If in Thread: ❌ Thread doesn’t know which object lock to release
✅ Hence placed in Object class

